  "diary": "Monday felt long but good. Woke up early to coffee and the kind of silence you get before the city really starts moving. The commute to Ballard was smooth—avoided the Light Rail mess by driving, which meant I caught the tail end of rush hour instead of fighting it. The ER was steady all day, nothing catastrophic, just the usual parade of minor injuries and complaints. I heard people talking about the World Cup match at lunch, bars getting packed downtown, but I was too focused on charting and triaging. By evening, I needed to move. Hit the gym while the sun was still painting everything gold, and my body felt grateful for it. Home now, stretched out with some tea, a video game I've been picking at for weeks, and a few letters I've been meaning to write. The brewing equipment in the closet is calling for attention soon—maybe this weekend.",
  "thought_process": "I chose efficiency today without overthinking it. The Light Rail closure didn't stress me because driving Ballard is routine; I just accepted the trade-off early. Work consumed most of my mental energy, so I didn't have bandwidth to join the World Cup buzz downtown—that felt like someone else's Monday. The gym was non-negotiable; I needed to burn off the accumulated tension from back-to-back shifts last week, and the weather was too perfect to waste. By evening I was tired but not depleted, so I let myself slow down with low-stakes activities: gaming and letters. There's something about handwriting that feels restorative after a day of screens and urgency. I'm aware my mood stayed even-keeled today—not elated, not drained—just present and methodical. That's the nurse in me.",
